<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="542" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" box="[151,1031,325,350]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,325,350]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Description.</emphasis>
Coloration typical, females similar to males or somewhat lighter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Penis with ventral margin convex in side view and with side margins uneven or serrated in ventral view (Figs. 95–96). Lower appendage of dorsal connective bifurcated, with branches of equal length, diverging, parallel, or bent inwards (Figs. 96–98). Style more or less expanded in distal half, with wedge-shaped tip (Figs. 99–100).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" box="[199,942,469,494]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
Body length (including tegmina): ♂, 4.0– 
<quantity box="[665,753,470,494]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" unit="mm" value="4.7">4.7 mm</quantity>
; ♀, 4.5–5.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
Differs from all other species by shape of lower appendage of dorsal connective. Only species feeding on 
<taxonomicName authority="Opiz" authorityName="Opiz" box="[151,269,541,565]" class="Eudicots" family="Betulaceae" genus="Duschekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,269,541,565]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Duschekia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,743,577,602]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" box="[199,743,577,602]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,577,602]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Host.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Opiz" authorityName="Opiz" box="[269,494,577,601]" class="Eudicots" family="Betulaceae" genus="Duschekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="fruticosa">
<emphasis box="[269,494,577,601]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Duschekia fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Opiz" authorityName="Opiz" box="[548,736,578,601]" class="Eudicots" family="Betulaceae" genus="Duschekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="maximowiczii">
<emphasis box="[548,736,578,601]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">D. maximowiczii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="542" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,613,638]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Distribution.</emphasis>
Northern Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Ossiannilsson" box="[566,798,613,638]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" refString="Ossiannilsson, F. (1981) The Auchenorrhyncha (Homoptera) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Part 2: Families Cicadidae, Cercopidae, Membracidae and Cicadellidae (exc. Deltocephalinae). Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, 7, 223 - 593." type="journal article" year="1981">Ossiannilsson, 1981</bibRefCitation>
); 
<collectingCountry box="[820,899,613,638]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Russia</collectingCountry>
: Northern part of European 
<collectingCountry box="[1218,1295,613,638]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Russia</collectingCountry>
, Siberia, the Russian Far East including 
<collectingRegion box="[459,557,649,674]" country="Russia" name="Sakhalin" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Sakhalin</collectingRegion>
and Kurile Islands; 
<collectingCountry box="[784,852,650,673]" name="Japan" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Japan</collectingCountry>
: Honshu (as 
<taxonomicName authority="Anufriev, 1967" authorityName="Anufriev" authorityYear="1967" box="[997,1332,649,674]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sardescens">
<emphasis box="[997,1153,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">O. sardescens</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Anufriev" box="[1160,1332,649,674]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" refString="Anufriev, G. A. (1967) Notes on the genus Oncopsis Burmeister, 1838 (Homoptera, Auchenorrhyncha) with descriptions of new species from the Soviet Far East. Entomologisk Tidskrift. 88, 174 - 184." type="journal article" year="1967">Anufriev, 1967</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayashi" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" refString="Hayashi, M. &amp; Higashikawa, O. (1997) Homoptera-Auchenorrhyncha and Heteroptera (Insecta, Rhynchota) from Sugadaira, Central Honshu, Japan. Bulletin of Sugadaira Montane Research Center, 14, 15 - 56." type="journal article" year="1997">Hayashi &amp; Higashikawa, 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="542" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,721,746]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[324,484,721,745]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sardescens">
<emphasis box="[324,484,721,745]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">O. sardescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from the Russian Far East (
<bibRefCitation author="Anufriev" box="[985,1163,721,746]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" refString="Anufriev, G. A. (1967) Notes on the genus Oncopsis Burmeister, 1838 (Homoptera, Auchenorrhyncha) with descriptions of new species from the Soviet Far East. Entomologisk Tidskrift. 88, 174 - 184." type="journal article" year="1967">Anufriev, 1967</bibRefCitation>
); two years later it was lowered in rank to a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lauterer &amp; Anufriev, 1969" authorityName="Lauterer &amp; Anufriev" authorityYear="1969" box="[544,1027,757,782]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planiscuta">
<emphasis box="[544,696,757,781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">O. planiscuta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lauterer" box="[710,1018,757,782]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" refString="Lauterer, P. &amp; Anufriev, G. A. (1969) Contribution to the knowledge of the genus Oncopsis Burm. (Homoptera, Cicadellidae) from China and Far East. Acta Musei Moraviae, 54, 161 - 168." type="journal article" year="1969">Lauterer &amp; Anufriev, 1969</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. In 
<bibRefCitation author="Anufriev" box="[1069,1253,757,782]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" refString="Anufriev, G. A. (1977) Leafhoppers (Homoptera, Auchenorrhyncha, Cicadellidae) of Kurile Islands. Trudy Zoologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR, 70, 10 - 36 [in Russian]." type="journal article" year="1977">Anufriev (1977)</bibRefCitation>
it appeared as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[365,516,793,817]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planiscuta">
<emphasis box="[365,516,793,817]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">O. planiscuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the first time, but without formal establishment of a synonymy (the note “syn. n.” after the species name, any explanations, etc.). The search in “Zoological Record” database returned no results concerning synonymy of these two species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,325,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1424565284" location="Sokol Town" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Sakhalin">
In males from the Southern 
<collectingRegion box="[517,615,904,929]" country="Russia" name="Sakhalin" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Sakhalin</collectingRegion>
(environs of 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:525E87C1115B7C40FF4A23A50A31B160:DF28600C115B7C40FCDD20B508A5B697" box="[768,908,904,929]" name="Sokol Town" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" stateProvince="Sakhalin">Sokol Town</location>
, from 
<taxonomicName authority="Opiz" authorityName="Opiz" box="[982,1172,905,928]" class="Eudicots" family="Betulaceae" genus="Duschekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="maximowiczii">
<emphasis box="[982,1172,905,928]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">D. maximowiczii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, recording at 22–23o C) signals are unceasing trains of syllables lasting for 10-20 s (
<figureCitation box="[816,913,940,965]" captionStart="FIGURES 112 – 124" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1874,1897]" captionTargetBox="[175,1406,204,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[157,1421,193,1844]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 112 – 124. Oncopsis spp., oscillograms of male calling signals. 112 – 115 ― O. planiscuta (112 and 114 ― male from Sakhalin, 113 and 115 ― male from Irkutsk Area), 116 – 120 ― O. tristis (116 and 118 ― male from Sakhalin, 117 and 120 ― male from Moscow Area, 119 ― male from Altai Mts.), 121 – 124 ― O. abdykulovi sp. n. (121 – 123 ― recording at 19 - 20 o C, 124 ― recording at 29 o C). Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “ 114 – 115 ”, “ 118 ”, “ 120 ”, and “ 122 – 123 ” are given under the same numbers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242425/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Fig. 112</figureCitation>
). Calling signals of the only studied male from Siberia (environs of Nizhneudinsk, ca. 
<quantity box="[600,688,979,1004]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" unit="km" value="300.0">300 km</quantity>
West of 
<collectingRegion box="[794,876,979,1004]" country="Russia" name="Irkutsk" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Irkutsk</collectingRegion>
, from 
<taxonomicName authority="Opiz" authorityName="Opiz" box="[954,1090,979,1003]" class="Eudicots" family="Betulaceae" genus="Duschekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="fruticosa">
<emphasis box="[954,1090,979,1003]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">D. fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, recording at 27o C) consist of short trains of syllables separated by pauses (
<figureCitation box="[658,756,1014,1039]" captionStart="FIGURES 112 – 124" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1874,1897]" captionTargetBox="[175,1406,204,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[157,1421,193,1844]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 112 – 124. Oncopsis spp., oscillograms of male calling signals. 112 – 115 ― O. planiscuta (112 and 114 ― male from Sakhalin, 113 and 115 ― male from Irkutsk Area), 116 – 120 ― O. tristis (116 and 118 ― male from Sakhalin, 117 and 120 ― male from Moscow Area, 119 ― male from Altai Mts.), 121 – 124 ― O. abdykulovi sp. n. (121 – 123 ― recording at 19 - 20 o C, 124 ― recording at 29 o C). Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “ 114 – 115 ”, “ 118 ”, “ 120 ”, and “ 122 – 123 ” are given under the same numbers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242425/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Fig. 113</figureCitation>
). However, syllable shape and repetition period in signals of males from both localities are similar (
<figureCitation box="[618,788,1051,1076]" captionStart="FIGURES 112 – 124" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1874,1897]" captionTargetBox="[175,1406,204,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[157,1421,193,1844]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 112 – 124. Oncopsis spp., oscillograms of male calling signals. 112 – 115 ― O. planiscuta (112 and 114 ― male from Sakhalin, 113 and 115 ― male from Irkutsk Area), 116 – 120 ― O. tristis (116 and 118 ― male from Sakhalin, 117 and 120 ― male from Moscow Area, 119 ― male from Altai Mts.), 121 – 124 ― O. abdykulovi sp. n. (121 – 123 ― recording at 19 - 20 o C, 124 ― recording at 29 o C). Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “ 114 – 115 ”, “ 118 ”, “ 120 ”, and “ 122 – 123 ” are given under the same numbers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242425/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">Figs. 114–115</figureCitation>
); this supports the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName box="[1186,1342,1051,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planiscuta">
<emphasis box="[1186,1342,1051,1075]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">O. planiscuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sardescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="542">O. sardescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
